					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">1. Why is there no BCD support on the NES's 6502? I mean, I wouldn't of thought that it would of been to save cash. </div><br />It saves a considerable amount of transistors inside the chip. No idea why the decimal mode in particular was removed, but at least it is.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">2. Why did the NES have so many mappers, while the GameBoy only had a handful? </div><br />Mainly because 90% of iNES mappers are chineese pirates. The other 10% contain about 7% of custom made boards (like Konami, Sunsoft, Bandai and so on), and about 3% of mapper were officially made by Nintendo. The values here are just an evaluation by me to show you the main thing, not result of any exact calculation. In other word, 95% of games uses the last 3% of mappers. I think rich developpers think it would just be better to developp their own boards and mappers, to have a wider range of available features. Why this isn't done on the Game Boy, I have no idea. However, the Game Boy has better protection than the famicom (wich actually had none at all), I think the GameBoy has a bios that deals with checksum and so to verify the game is licenced. So yeah, the Famicom had no protection and that's why chinese have created lots of custom made pirated cart, and each one with it's own circuitry, so it's own mapper.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">3. Why aren't the NES's registers stored in Zero Page like they are on the Atari 2600? I know that the NES didn't have that much RAM, but what is 20 odd bytes lost when you can save so many cycles when accessing them. </div>
<br />This is just one thing Nintendo chosen, I think it would be wastefull to have an area stored in both RAM and register. That would means all registers are read-buffered (a la $2007), wich would tend to be somewhat annoying. Also, I think RAM is a much more usefull use of page-zero than registers, that are acessed somewhat rarely (well, that COULD save time in VBlank, but I don't think it'd make so much difference in the long term, and Nintendo didn't care about that when developping the Famicom).</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
