					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">WedNESday wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">then at which part of the cycle (0/3, 1/3, 2/3) does the write take place?</div>
<br />
<br />I'd guess not until the 2nd or 3rd (or possibly later?) -- though it probably varies depending on the circumstances.  I seem to recall blargg mentioning something about the NES has different startup states and the PPU syncs slightly differently with the CPU depending on which state is "chosen" at startup.
<br />
<br />But I don't really know.  I don't think the exact behavior of this is known.
<br />
<br />From an emulator standpoint, this isn't really something I'd worry about anyway.  The worst case scenario is 2 or 3 pixels which are "wrong" at a time when there will always be shaking anyway so you won't even notice that the 2 pixels are off.  (it's impossible for a game to have timed writes to rely on said behavior because the CPU is just too slow -- so any time such a thing happens, the point on the screen at which the change takes place will shake around on the scanline -- see SMB3 status bar and MM3 enemy select screen... the distortion flickers around every frame -- so you can't tell whether or not it's 1 or 2 pixels off).</div>

